{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "13 — The Companion Domain: Quests, Life & Recaps",
  "description": "Balaur's personal-companion layer sits on top of the nodes spine: tasks (quests) carry a recurrence DSL, life measures log the owner's numeric and qualitative data, and the recap telescope collapses conversation history into progressively coarser summaries. This tour walks the recur DSL, the quest lifecycle, the nudge and briefing crons, the life log, the day assembly, the period telescope, and the idempotent catch-up and manual compaction paths.",
  "steps": [
    {
      "file": "internal/tasks/recur.go",
      "line": 34,
      "title": "13.1 — The recur DSL (pure)",
      "description": "```go\nfunc Parse(s string) (Rule, error)\n```\n\n`Parse` turns a short human string into a typed `Rule`. The four patterns are:\n\n- `\"daily\"` — every day\n- `\"every:3d\"` — every N days\n- `\"weekly:mon,thu\"` — specific weekdays (deduped, order kept)\n- `\"monthly:15\"` — a fixed day of the month (1-31, clamped to month length)\n\nThe function is pure: no PocketBase access, no time.Now(), no side effects. `Rule` carries only what is needed for the two operations that follow — `Matches` (does a candidate time fit the pattern?) and `Next` (what is the next occurrence?).\n\nThe zero `Rule` (`Kind == \"\"`) means one-off: tasks start as one-offs unless the owner gives a recur string. `IsZero()` is the canonical test.\n\nAGENTS.md: *deterministic, offline, free behaviour is the default.* The entire recurrence engine runs without a model and without network access."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/tasks/recur.go",
      "line": 85,
      "title": "13.2 — Skip-forward occurrence math",
      "description": "```go\nfunc Next(r Rule, due, after time.Time) time.Time\n```\n\n`Next` returns the first occurrence strictly after `after`, anchored on `due` for the wall-clock time of day. All arithmetic happens in `due`'s `Location` — callers pass box-local times so DST is handled by `AddDate` (which preserves wall clock across transitions, unlike duration arithmetic).\n\nThe skip-forward (org-mode `++`) contract is important: when `after` is far past `due` — say, a weekly task that was not ticked for three weeks — the result lands **once in the future**, never producing a backlog of missed runs the owner must click through. This is a deliberate product trade-off: completions model intent, not obligation.\n\nFor `monthly`, the anchor walks month-firsts and `monthlyOn` clamps the requested day to the month's length. `monthly:31` therefore visits February 28 and is back on the 31st in March — no `AddDate` overflow drift.\n\nThe weekly path walks day by day with `AddDate(0,0,1)` and checks `Weekday()` — simple and correct; the loop terminates within 7 iterations."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/tasks/tasks.go",
      "line": 30,
      "title": "13.3 — Creating a quest",
      "description": "```go\nfunc Create(app core.App, o CreateOpts) (*core.Record, error)\n```\n\nA task is a `type=task` node in the unified `nodes` collection. `Create` stores the title, notes, recur string, and due time as node props — there is no separate tasks table. Tasks, measures, and day nodes all live on the same spine; **Tour 14** covers `internal/nodes` and the graph in depth.\n\nThe key pre-save step is `normalizeRecur`: a calendar-pattern rule (`weekly`/`monthly`) is the truth, not whatever date the owner happened to pick. If the due date misses the pattern — say, a `weekly:mon` task created on a Wednesday — `Create` snaps the due forward to the next Monday (same wall-clock time), keeping the schedule self-consistent from the first occurrence.\n\nOwner consent is the only gate: unlike memories there is no proposal step. A wrong task is one `Drop` away. The audit entry lands strictly after the successful save (`store.Audit` is called last), following the AGENTS.md invariant: *audit strictly AFTER the successful write, never before.*"
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/tasks/tasks.go",
      "line": 189,
      "title": "13.4 — Completion: one-offs close, recurring advance",
      "description": "```go\nfunc Done(app core.App, rec *core.Record, now time.Time) (DoneResult, error)\n```\n\n`Done` branches on whether the task has a recurrence rule:\n\n**One-off:** props `state` becomes `\"done\"`, `done_at` is stamped, the record is saved. Simple close.\n\n**Recurring:** the function computes the next due with `Next`, deletes `nudged_at` and `snoozed_until` from props (so the nudger treats the new due as fresh), and wraps both the completion entry write and the record save in `app.RunInTransaction` — if the process dies between them the task still reads as due and the nudger re-fires on the next tick. The audit lands outside the transaction: a failed audit never rolls back the completion.\n\n`recur_from_done` shifts the anchor to `now` instead of the old `due`, modelling habit-style tasks where the next occurrence is relative to when you actually did it, not when you were supposed to. Calendar-pattern rules (`weekly`/`monthly`) reject `recur_from_done` at create time — their pattern is the anchor, not the completion moment.\n\nEarly completion (owner finishes before the due time) advances `after` past the current due so the just-satisfied occurrence is never re-nudged."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/tasks/nudge.go",
      "line": 85,
      "title": "13.5 — Nudge and briefing crons",
      "description": "```go\nfunc Nudge(app core.App, client llm.Client, now time.Time) error\n```\n\n`Nudge` fires every due reminder as **one** assistant message (origin `\"nudge\"`) in the master conversation — one interruption, not one per task. The message text is model-composed in Balaur's voice when a client is available; a deterministic list is both the no-model default and the failure fallback. Idempotency is derived from `nudged_at` in each task's props: a task that already carries a `nudged_at` for the current due window is excluded by `DueForNudge` — no separate state table.\n\nThe companion to `Nudge` is `Briefing` in `internal/tasks/briefing.go` (line 46). `Briefing` fires once per local day after a configurable hour: it greets the owner with overdue items, today's commitments, and yesterday's log. Its idempotency is also derived — from whether an `origin=briefing` message exists since local midnight. A quiet day (no overdue, no today) produces no message: the companion does not manufacture noise.\n\nBoth functions follow the AGENTS.md rule: *deterministic, offline, free behaviour is the default* — the model path is opt-in, the deterministic path always succeeds."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/life/life.go",
      "line": 61,
      "title": "13.6 — The life log",
      "description": "```go\nfunc Log(app core.App, o LogOpts) (*core.Record, error)\n```\n\nOwner-defined measures — weight, mood, steps, sleep, anything — are stored as `type=measure` nodes. The measure `kind` is a free-form string normalised to lowercase; the owner invents their own vocabulary. `noted_at` is the chronological truth: you can log yesterday's weight today and it files correctly.\n\nSystem kinds (`\"completion\"`, `\"journal\"`) are reserved and rejected here — they enter through their own verbs (`task_done`, `journal.write`) to keep the audit trail unambiguous.\n\nThe `value_num` field carries numeric values (weight, steps); `unit` carries the unit string; `body` carries free text. All three are optional — a mood log might carry only a text description, a step count only a number.\n\nThe owner's statement is the consent; corrections go through `Drop`. There is no proposal step here either — life logging is immediate and reversible."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/life/day.go",
      "line": 29,
      "title": "13.7 — A day, assembled",
      "description": "```go\nfunc Day(app core.App, conversationID string, d time.Time) (DayData, error)\n```\n\n`Day` assembles everything that belongs to a calendar day into one `DayData` struct: the journal (the `type=day` node's body, if non-empty), logged measures and done tasks via `Range`, and the day recap summary if one exists.\n\nThe journal lives in `internal/life/journal.go`. `JournalWrite` (line 23) keeps the owner's words verbatim as the body of the `type=day` node — one node per calendar date, keyed on `props.date = YYYY-MM-DD`. Multiple writes in the same day **append** to that node's body (blank-line separated); the first write creates the node via `nodes.DayNode`. This append-only design means journal writes are safe to re-order and never overwrite earlier entries.\n\n`Range` (the shared aggregator) is the single query that feeds both the day view and the period-node aggregator — the day and period lenses never drift because they share code, not copy it. AGENTS.md: *one source of truth per concern.*"
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/recap/periods.go",
      "line": 11,
      "title": "13.8 — The period telescope",
      "description": "```go\ntype Period struct {\n    Type  string // day | week | month | quarter | year\n    Start time.Time\n    End   time.Time\n}\n```\n\nThe telescope is the key mental model for recaps: as the owner scrolls up past today, the past appears as progressively coarser summaries — days for the current week, weeks for the last month, months for the last quarter, and so on.\n\n`Period` is a simple value type: a type tag and an inclusive `Start` / exclusive `End` in the owner's timezone. The five builder functions (`Day`, `Week`, `Month`, `Quarter`, `Year` — lines 47-70) construct the period containing any given `time.Time`, each via its `*Start` helper. All boundaries snap to local midnight so what counts as \"Tuesday\" follows the box's clock, not UTC.\n\n`Week` uses ISO weeks (`weekStart`, Monday 00:00). `Quarter` uses calendar quarters (`quarterStart`: Jan-Mar, Apr-Jun, …). Periods always start on a month/quarter/year boundary, so there is no day-of-month clamping here — `End` is just `Start.AddDate(0, n, 0)`, which carries calendar overflow correctly.\n\n`childType` defines the expand-down direction: weeks and months both expand to days (sidestepping weeks that straddle month boundaries), quarters to months, years to quarters. `ParentType` defines the breadcrumb path upward — a week's parent is the month it starts in, not the quarter."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/recap/generate.go",
      "line": 306,
      "title": "13.9 — Idempotent catch-up",
      "description": "```go\nfunc EnsureSummaries(ctx context.Context, app core.App, client llm.Client, conversationID string, now time.Time) error\n```\n\n`EnsureSummaries` walks every period from the oldest message to now, bottom-up (days first, then weeks, months, quarters, years), and generates any missing summary. Two mechanisms keep it safe to call repeatedly:\n\n1. **Existence short-circuit:** `ensureOne` checks whether a summary already exists before calling the model. An already-written summary is never regenerated.\n2. **High-water marks:** persisted timestamps record how far each walk has progressed. The day loop stores the last contiguously-settled day; the parent loop stores the last contiguously-settled fully-past period of each type (week, month, quarter, year) independently — a period whose generation produced nothing holds the mark so the next run retries it. On the next run each walk resumes from its own mark rather than `oldest`, making steady-state ticks O(1) Finds per period type instead of O(all history). Only fully-past periods (`End <= now`) are marked — the still-open current period keeps getting re-evaluated as new content arrives. A stale mark can only skip summaries that already exist; the existence check remains the safety net. Marks are stamped with the owner timezone; a timezone change invalidates them, so the next run re-walks from oldest and re-keys summaries under the new zone.\n\nErrors abort the run; the next cron retries from the saved marks.\n\nAGENTS.md: *deterministic, offline, free behaviour is the default* — when no `client` is available the cron skips generation silently rather than erroring."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/recap/compact.go",
      "line": 34,
      "title": "13.10 — Manual compaction",
      "description": "```go\nfunc DraftToday(ctx context.Context, app core.App, client llm.Client, conv *core.Record, now time.Time) (string, int, time.Time, error)\nfunc CommitToday(app core.App, conv *core.Record, summary string, draftedThrough, now time.Time) error\n```\n\nManual compaction is the owner-driven, mid-day counterpart to the overnight recap. It is a two-step declinable proposal — the owner reviews and optionally edits the `DraftToday` output in a modal before `CommitToday` writes anything. This matches the AGENTS.md pattern for every Balaur mutation: *capability pushed through explicit, owner-consented steps.*\n\n`DraftToday` summarises today's not-yet-compacted turns (since local midnight, or since the last `compacted_through` boundary, whichever is later) and returns the proposed text without persisting anything, plus the drafted-through time — the exclusive end of the summarised window — that the caller MUST hold and pass to `CommitToday`. If there is nothing new it returns `\"\"` with count 0 and the caller shows a gentle note instead of an empty draft.\n\n`CommitToday` appends a dated section (`[15:04 compact] …`) to the conversation's rolling `summary` field and advances `compacted_through` to the drafted-through time — not the commit-click time — so messages that arrive while the review modal is open stay in context instead of being silently forgotten; the `[15:04 compact]` label still stamps the commit moment. The key invariant is **append, never rewrite**: the owner can compact several times in one day and each fold is preserved as a distinct section. An empty approved summary is a no-op — a blank accept cannot wipe the thread. A missing, future, or boundary-preceding `draftedThrough` is rejected with an error rather than silently falling back to `now`. The audit entry lands strictly after the successful save.\n\nThe live chat dock and model context skip past `compacted_through` (via `RecentTurns`), so compacted turns no longer consume context window — the transcript itself is kept intact for the record."
    }
  ]
}
